Candlestick Charts¶

Using matplotlib.finance.

back to index

In [18]:
from matplotlib.finance import candlestick_ohlc # Open, High, Low, Close
from matplotlib.dates import (
    DateFormatter,
    date2num,
    WeekdayLocator,
    DayLocator,
    MONDAY
)
In [19]:
def make_candles(ticks, title, figsize, year_month):
    ticks_reset = ticks.loc[year_month].reset_index()
    ticks_reset['date_ax'] = ticks_reset['Date'].apply(
        lambda date: date2num(date)
    )

    columns = ['date_ax', 'Open', 'High', 'Low', 'Close']
    quotes = [tuple(vals) for vals in ticks_reset[columns].values]
    
    mondays = WeekdayLocator(MONDAY)        # major ticks on the mondays
    alldays = DayLocator()                  # minor ticks on the days
    weekFormatter = DateFormatter('%b %d')  # e.g., Jan 12
    dayFormatter = DateFormatter('%d')      # e.g., 12
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=figsize)
    fig.subplots_adjust(bottom=0.2)
    ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(mondays)
    ax.xaxis.set_minor_locator(alldays)
    ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(weekFormatter)
    
    candlestick_ohlc(ax, quotes, width=0.6, colorup='g', colordown='r')

    plt.title(title);
In [20]:
make_candles(tesla_ticks, 'Tesla ticks, January 2015', (20, 10), '2015-01')

Basic Financial Analysis¶

Daily Percentage Change¶

$ r_t = \frac{p_t}{p_{t-1}} -1$

If daily returns have a wide distribution, the stock is more volatile from one day to the next.

back to index

In [23]:
# Manually
tesla_ticks['Returns'] = (
    tesla_ticks['Close'] / tesla_ticks['Close'].shift(1)
) - 1

# OR using Pandas in-built function 
ford_ticks['Returns'] = ford_ticks['Close'].pct_change(1)
gm_ticks['Returns'] = gm_ticks['Close'].pct_change(1)

Cumulative Return (CMR)¶

$ i_t = (1+r_t) * i_{t-1} $

where $ i_t $ - investment at time $ t $, $ r_t $ - return at time $ t $.

Aggregate amount an investment has gained or lost over time.

In [28]:
for df in [tesla_ticks, ford_ticks, gm_ticks]:
    df['CMR'] = (1 + df['Returns']).cumprod()
In [29]:
tesla_ticks['CMR'].plot(
